bug.cf_doc_type: If docs needed, set a value

Installed Packages Name : antimicro Arch : x86_64 Epoch : 0 Version : 2.23 Release : 1.fc25 Size : 3.6 M Repo : @System From repo : updates Summary : Graphical program used to map keyboard buttons and mouse controls to a gamepad URL : https://github.com/AntiMicro/antimicro License : GPLv3+ Description : AntiMicro is a graphical program used to map keyboard keys and mouse controls : to a gamepad. This program is useful for playing PC games using a gamepad that : do not have any form of built-in gamepad support. AntiMicro was inspired by : QJoyPad but has additional features. I created new user, and was able to reproduce. I wanted to confirm there was nothing in my profile causing the issue. This is on a laptop, I am unable to confirm on my desktop. The only notable differences I can think of is it has an Nvidia low end graphics card running Nvidia drivers. Also joystick is plugged into usb 2.0, and laptop only has 3.0.

I have tested this as multiple users, including root and all exhibit the same behavior. One thing I did notice, is if I load antimicro or qjoypad and setup keys, I can join a game and they will work, until I hold a key to long and then it crashes. However doing this on the command line does not result in any keys being pressed in the terminal. However if as root I run startx manually it works in the terminal and no crash or errors are seen. I am happy to provide any more information if requested

Well, I wanted to confirm this was not something stupid I have done. So I booted to the F25 Live image on USB. I installed antimicro. I set one button to a keyboard letter (k). I pressed the button on the joystick and boom X crashed. This is 100% reproducible on Live image at least on my laptop hardware. I am happy to help with any debugging with some direction. Following these instructions from https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/How_to_debug_Wayland_problems Testing under different compositors If you experience a problem with a Wayland app, it is very useful to know whether the problem is present under just a single compositor (in that case it's likely a compositor bug) or under multiple compositors (in that case it's likely an app/toolkit bug). Please run your session with the reference Weston compositor and try to reproduce the issue. You can either run Weston as a nested window, or as a full session. First, install weston package (you can read many useful information in its man page): $ sudo dnf install weston Then create a config file which will specify that you want to have XWayland support enabled in your weston sessions. Create ~/.config/weston.ini with this contents: [core] modules=xwayland.so Now you can start weston either as nested window or as a full session. To start a nested Weston window, run this from a terminal: $ weston A Weston window should open and you should see and a terminal icon in its top left corner. Use that icon to launch a terminal and from that you can run apps and other commands using Weston. Exit the compositor by simply closing the window or killing the weston process. To start a full Weston session (not nested inside another X11 or Wayland session), switch to a free VT (Ctrl+Alt+Fx) and run: $ weston-launch ---------------------------------------------------------- Resulted in [matt.lewis@snoopy ~]$ antimicro The X11 connection broke (error 1). Did the X11 server die? QObject::killTimer: Timers cannot be stopped from another thread QObject::~QObject: Timers cannot be stopped from another thread [matt.lewis@snoopy ~]$

Found work around, by disabling Xwayland edit /etc/gdm/custom.conf and un-comment line below #WaylandEnable=false ---------- init 3 init 5 login and now I can use my joystick with antimicro I will be running Xorg for now, if anyone needs anything I am happy to switch back and test. I provided everything I can think of, happy to provide more. Thanks,
yeap, reproduced.
Possible fix here: https://patchwork.freedesktop.org/series/20315/

(In reply to penguinbait from comment #11) > I installed these packages this morning and I am now experiencing the exact > same behavior using Xwayland. So, you mean, it works? > However I am confused. GDM is still disabling Xwayland, but WAYLAND_DISPLAY > is set, but Xorg is running? > > I have no idea what is happening? lol > > [matt.lewis@snoopy ~]$ cat /etc/gdm/custom.conf > # GDM configuration storage > > [daemon] > # Uncoment the line below to force the login screen to use Xorg > WaylandEnable=false There ^^^^ you have Wayland disabled in gdm config, that might explain why Wayland is not enabled?
Note, AFAIK the fix (comment 10) has landed in git upstream but is not yet available in fedora packages.

No, I still have wayland disabled in GDM. But I now appear to be running wayland? So its not working for me. Because it seems like I am no longer running Xorg? I am not sure why. However the only workaround I have now is to switch to run level 3 and startx if I want to play a game. [matt.lewis@snoopy ~]$ echo $WAYLAND_DISPLAY wayland-0 [matt.lewis@snoopy ~]$ ps -fe | grep Xorg gdm 1615 1612 0 19:26 tty1 00:00:00 /usr/libexec/Xorg vt1 -displayfd 3 -auth /run/user/42/gdm/Xauthority -nolisten tcp -background none -noreset -keeptty -verbose 3 I guess this appears to be another bug, where I have WaylandEnable=false, and while GDM is running Xord, but my session is running Xwayland.
Sorry you lost me there... Long story short, you need a fix in Xwayland which is not yet packaged. As to why you are using Wayland, are you sure you picked "GNOME on Xorg" in gdm as your session?

All I did was set WaylandEnable=false in /etc/gdm/custom.conf [matt.lewis@snoopy ~]$ cat /etc/gdm/custom.conf # GDM configuration storage [daemon] # Uncoment the line below to force the login screen to use Xorg WaylandEnable=false This allowed me to run Xorg when it booted up. After yesterdays updates its no longer honoring this setting and I am running Xorg in gdm, and Xwayland for my windowed session. I understand this fix is not packaged yet, do you have any idea when this will make it into updates? Should I open another bug report? Would that be for gdm ? Thanks
